VCS, git – what and why?

  • What is “version control”, and why should you care? Version control is a system that records changes to a file or set of files over time so that you can recall specific versions later. [Git book 1.1]

  • It allows you to revert selected files back to a previous state, revert the entire project back to a previous state, compare changes over time, see who last modified something that might be causing a problem, who introduced an issue and when, and more. Using a VCS also generally means that if you screw things up or lose files, you can easily recover. In addition, you get all this for very little overhead. [Git book 1.1]

  • git is a system (program) which is an example of VCS

git vs GitHub

A version control system for creating repositories

Hosting service allowing users to keep their repositories and manage them there. There are numerous other examples of similar services, e.g. GitLab or BitBucket.

Ways of interacting with git

Interacting with git is done by using commands (elementary actions). There are several ways of interacting with git:

  • Command line interface (CLI) – the most direct way.
  • Graphical user interface (GUI) built-in in some programming environment ( Visual Studio Code, JetBrains’ IDEs, RStudio).
  • Programmable interface – writing code in specific language using provided tools (usethis R package).
  • External desktop apps (SourceTree, GitKraken).
  • Website apps (GitHub website).

Basic git definitions

  • Repository – a copy of files of which the project consists.
  • Local/Remote – repository present on current machine/repository available via the network.
  • Diff – a change between two versions of the same file.
  • Commit – a git object, a snapshot of your entire repository.
  • SHA – hashed value of your commit, (almost) unique representation of your commit
  • Stage/Index – changes in local repository marked as ready to be commited.
  • Branch – a lightweight movable pointer to a commit.

Basic git commands

  • Init – initialize a new, empty repository.
  • Clone – create a new repository copying some existing repository.
  • Add/Stage – mark changes in local files as ready to be commited.
  • Commit – create a new commit from staged changes and add it to commit tree.
  • Pull – copy changes from local repository to remote.
  • Push – copy changes from remote repository to local.
  • Branch – create a new branch of commit tree.
  • Merge – combine changes from two distinct histories.
  • Checkout – change your position within the commit tree.

RStudio git GUI allows you to:

  • Browse through changes and compare files.
  • Pull/push changes from/to remote repository.

GitHub website GUI

GitHub website GUI

GitHub website allows you to:

  • Browse through public repositories, their files and commits.
  • Set up new repositories.
  • Clone a repository (create a new local from remote).
  • Fork a repository (create a new remote from remote).
  • Upload/modify files (but you shouldn’t).
  • Open issues (bug reports, feature suggestions, etc.).
  • Open and manage pull requests (merge branches within a repository and between repositories)
  • Do much more cool things.

A few words on branching

There are a few branching strategies which determine how branches are created and maintained within a project. There is no one universal best system, their usefulness usually depends on the project.

  • Single branch: main.
  • Main + one branch per team member.
  • Main + one branch per functionality fix/change (trunk-based workflow).
  • Main + devel + releases + features + fixes (git flow workflow).

Popular branching strategies: one branch

Repository with a single branch. All commits to main

Suitable for: small projects maintained by one person (my masters) or very small, short term projects by two-three person

Popular branching strategies: team member branches

Repository with a single main branch and one branch per each team member. Everyone works on their changes and then merge it into main and merge main into their branch to work further.

Suitable for: small/medium projects performed by by small teams without a need of constantly presetning the results of the projects to the client.

Popular branching strategies: trunk-based workflow

Repository with a single core trunk or main branch. A lot of small branches (adding and integrating one function, one step of workflow, one bugfix, one document, etc.) are constantly created, merged and deleted.

Suitable for: same as above (it is actually easier to maintain!); also suitable for medium and bigger open-source projects and the professional ones (web applications, R packages)

Popular branching strategies: trunk-based workflow

(source: toptal)

Popular branching strategies: git flow workflow

The most advanced workflow:

  • Main branch containing current “official”, representative version of the project, which is publicly available and possibly installed in the production environment.
  • Devel branch containing the development version, not necessarily ready and tested, but including changes to be further merged into main.
  • Feature branches containing single functionalities, later merged into devel.
  • Hotfix branches merged directly into main, being the results of fixing bugs found in already deployed solution.
  • Release branches being the step in between devel and main.

Suitable for: mostly for big teams with solutions which need constant deployment and integration; recently losing popularity to the previous solution.
